{"cursor":"27120","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Mechanism design' (sometimes called 'reverse game theory' [http://staff.science.uva.nl/~ulle/teaching/mas/slides/mas-\nmechanism-design-4up.pdf \"Multiagent Systems\"], from the University of\nAmsterdam. ) is a field in game theory studying solution concepts for a\nclass of private information games. The distinguishing features of these\ngames are:\n\n* that a game \"designer\" chooses the game structure rather than inheriting one\n\n* that the designer is interested in the game's outcome\n\nSuch a game is called a \"game of mechanism design\" and is usually solved by\nmotivating agents to disclose their private information. The 2007 Nobel Memorial\nPrize in Economic Sciences was awarded to Leonid Hurwicz, Eric Maskin, and Roger\nMyerson \"for having laid the foundations of mechanism design theory\".\n","linknr":440,"url":"Mechanism_design","recorded":1362478826,"links":26,"instances":[],"pdf":["http://staff.science.uva.nl/~ulle/teaching/mas/slides/mas-mechanism-design-4up.pdf"],"categories":["Game theory","Social choice theory","Mechanism design|*"],"headings":["Intuition","Foundations","Highlighted results","Examples","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/c/c9/Stanley_Reiter_MDdiagram.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/8/f/78fb652a2e06bbad99d4b54531029c40.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/9/4f9663a883ddb48b0d26af28f8cf327b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/9/6/69691c7bdcc3ce6d5d8a1361f22d04ac.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/2/f/b2f5ff47436671b6e533d8dc3614845d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/5/d/e5d14c394300b7fa0a720200a8127311.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/9/4f9663a883ddb48b0d26af28f8cf327b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/0/d/50d91f80cbb8feda1d10e167107ad1ff.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/8/f/78fb652a2e06bbad99d4b54531029c40.png","//upload.wik